		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>What is Apex Batch Class in Salesforce?</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In Salesforce development, handling <strong>large data volumes</strong> efficiently is a common challenge. This is where the <strong>Apex Batch Class</strong> comes into play. A Batch Apex allows developers to process <strong>millions of records asynchronously</strong> without hitting governor limits.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Unlike a trigger or synchronous class, a Batch Apex job runs in chunks (batches) of records, making it perfect for long-running or data-intensive operations. Salesforce automatically manages the execution so that resources are optimized and performance remains stable.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Key Benefits of Using Apex Batch Class</strong></h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->
<ol class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Handles Large Data Volumes</strong> – Processes records in manageable chunks.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Scalable &amp; Efficient</strong> – Perfect for enterprises dealing with big data.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Asynchronous Execution</strong> – Runs in the background without interrupting users.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Error Handling</strong> – Provides clear control over failures in each batch.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Flexibility</strong> – Can be scheduled, monitored, and chained with other jobs.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Core Concepts of Batch Apex</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>The Role of Database.Batchable Interface</strong></h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Every Apex Batch Class must implement the Database.Batchable interface. This interface defines how Salesforce processes batches of records.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>The Three Mandatory Methods</strong></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->
<ol class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Start()</strong> – Collects the records to be processed.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Execute()</strong> – Runs on each batch of records.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Finish()</strong> – Performs final operations after all batches are processed.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Batch Size Considerations</strong></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Default size: 200 records per batch.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Can range between 1 to 2,000 records.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Choose based on complexity and performance needs.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Step-by-Step Guide to Writing an Apex Batch Class</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Setting Up a Batch Class in Salesforce</strong></h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A typical batch class starts with:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:code -->
<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>
global class mySampleBatchApex implements Database.Batchable&lt;SObject> {
    
    // We hardcode the desired value here in a static variable.
    private static final String TARGET_RATING = 'Hot';

    // 1) start():
    public Database.QueryLocator start(Database.BatchableContext bc) {
        // WHY: Excluding already‑'Hot' reduces DML and avoids needless row locking.
        return Database.getQueryLocator(&#91;
            SELECT Id, Rating
            FROM Account
            WHERE Rating = NULL OR Rating != :TARGET_RATING
        ]);
    }

    // 2) execute(): bulk‑safe update of the current scope.
    public void execute(Database.BatchableContext bc, List&lt;Account> scope) {
        if (scope.isEmpty()) return; // If scope is empty better not to execute: no work, no DML.

         List&lt;Account> accountsToUpdate = new List&lt;Account>(); // create a list for all acccounts to be updated
        for (Account a : scope) {
            // WHY: Double‑checking.
            if (a.Rating != TARGET_RATING) {
                a.Rating = TARGET_RATING;
                accountsToUpdate.add(a); // add to the above created list
            }
        }

        if (!accountsToUpdate.isEmpty()) {
            // WHY: allOrNone=false so one failure doesn't abort the whole chunk.
            Database.update(accountsToUpdate, /* allOrNone */ false); // performing database.update outside the for loop.
        }
    }

    // 3) finish(): good place for logging or notifications; kept simple here.
    public void finish(Database.BatchableContext bc) {
        System.debug(LoggingLevel.INFO, 'mySampleBatchApex finished. All Accounts set to \'' + TARGET_RATING + '\'.');
    }
}
</code></pre>
<!-- /wp:code -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Running/Executing a Batch Job from Developer Console Anynomous window: </strong></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":2427,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://thetechnologyfiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/execute_batch_apex_anonymous_window-1-1024x554.webp" alt="apex batch class" class="wp-image-2427"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>mySampleBatchApex batch = new mySampleBatchApex();<br>Database.executeBatch(batch, 200);</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Monitoring and Debugging</strong></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Go to <strong>Setup → Apex Jobs</strong> to track status.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Use <strong>System.debug()</strong> for troubleshooting.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":2429,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://thetechnologyfiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/apex-jobs-in-quick-find-1024x338.webp" alt="check scheduled apex batch class from here" class="wp-image-2429"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Now, lets schedule this batch job to run daily at 2 AM</strong></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Create another scheduler apex class -> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:code -->
<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>public class mySampleBatchApexScheduler implements Schedulable {
    
    private final Integer scopeSize;

    public mySampleBatchApexScheduler() { this(200); }
    public mySampleBatchApexScheduler(Integer scopeSize) {
        // Keep defaults sensible; batch scope of 200 is typical.
        this.scopeSize = (scopeSize == null || scopeSize &lt;= 0) ? 200 : scopeSize;
    }

    public void execute(SchedulableContext sc) {
        Database.executeBatch(new mySampleBatchApex(), scopeSize);
    }

}</code></pre>
<!-- /wp:code -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Running/Scheduling a Batch Job from Developer Console Anynomous window: </strong></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As we can see that we have provided the 'cron expression' to set the timings and executed the highlighted code to schedule our apex batch job.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":2438,"width":"1035px","height":"auto","sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-resized"><img src="https://thetechnologyfiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/apex-batch-job-scheduler-2-1024x555.webp" alt="apex batch class" class="wp-image-2438" style="width:1035px;height:auto"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Monitoring and Debugging</strong></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Go to <strong>Setup → Scheduled Jobs</strong> to track status.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":2440,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://thetechnologyfiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/scheduled-job-2-1024x560.webp" alt="" class="wp-image-2440"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Real-World Use Cases of Apex Batch Class</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->
<ol class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Data Cleansing &amp; Deduplication</strong> – Remove duplicates in millions of records.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Mass Updates</strong> – Recalculate fields like revenue or territory assignments.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Integrations</strong> – Sync large data sets with external systems.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Best Practices for Apex Batch Class</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Use <strong>selective SOQL queries</strong> to avoid unnecessary records.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Implement <strong>try-catch blocks</strong> for error handling.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Break down jobs into <strong>smaller batches</strong> for better efficiency.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Always test in a <strong>sandbox</strong> before running in production.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Apex Batch Class vs Queueable Apex vs Future Methods</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">FeatureBatch ApexQueueable ApexFuture Methods</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">Records Handled Millions Limited Very Limited</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">Async Execution Yes Yes Yes</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">Chaining Yes Yes No</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">Monitoring Yes Yes No</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">✅ <strong>Use Batch Apex</strong> for heavy data jobs.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">✅ <strong>Use Queueable Apex</strong> for medium jobs needing chaining.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left">✅ <strong>Use Future Methods</strong> for lightweight background jobs.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Common Challenges and How to Solve Them</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->
<ol class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Governor Limits</strong> → Use efficient queries.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Debugging Large Jobs</strong> → Add logging inside execute().</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Data Locking</strong> → Avoid updates on the same record in parallel jobs.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>FAQs about Apex Batch Class</strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Q1. What is the maximum number of batch jobs I can run in Salesforce?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>You can have up to <strong>5 queued or active batch jobs</strong> at a time.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Q2. Can I call a batch class from another batch?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Yes, but use <strong>Queueable Apex</strong> for chaining batch jobs effectively.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Q3. What is the maximum batch size in Salesforce?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The maximum batch size is <strong>2,000 records</strong>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Q4. How do I monitor batch jobs?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Navigate to <strong>Setup → Apex Jobs</strong> for job details.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Q5. Is Apex Batch Class synchronous or asynchronous?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>It is always <strong>asynchronous</strong>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Q6. Can I test batch classes in Apex test methods?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Yes, use Test.startTest() and Test.stopTest() to simulate batch execution.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Conclusion: </strong></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Why Every Developer Should Master Apex Batch Class</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The <strong>Apex Batch Class</strong> is one of the most powerful tools Salesforce offers for handling large datasets. By mastering its structure, best practices, and real-world applications, developers can build <strong>efficient, scalable, and error-resistant applications</strong>. Whether you’re cleaning data, syncing with external systems, or performing massive recalculations, <strong>Batch Apex is your go-to solution in 2025 and beyond</strong>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>🔗 Learn more from Salesforce’s official docs: <a target="_blank" href="https://developer.salesforce.com/docs/atlas.en-us.apexcode.meta/apexcode/apex_batch_interface.htm" rel="noreferrer noopener">Salesforce Apex Batch Apex Guide</a></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

